}

@article{angenentmari2019deep-9c2, 
  year     = {2019}, 
  keywords = {deep learning, {MPA}, Sort-Seq}, 
  title    = {Deep Learning for {RNA} Synthetic Biology}, 
  author   = {Angenent-Mari, Nicolaas and Garruss, Alexander and Soenksen, Luis Ruben and Church, George and Collins, James}, 
  journal  = {{bioRxiv}}, 
  doi      = {10.1101/872077}, 
  abstract = {Engineered {RNA} elements are programmable tools capable of detecting small molecules, proteins, and nucleic acids. Predicting the behavior of these tools remains a challenge, a situation that could be addressed through enhanced pattern recognition from deep learning. Thus, we investigate Deep Neural Networks ({DNN}) to predict toehold switch function as a canonical riboswitch model in synthetic biology. To facilitate {DNN} training, we synthesized and characterized in vivo a dataset of 91,534 toehold switches spanning 23 viral genomes and 906 human transcription factors. {DNNs} trained on nucleotide sequences outperformed (R2=0.43-0.70) previous state-of-the-art thermodynamic and kinetic models (R2=0.04-0.15) and allowed for human-understandable attention-visualizations ({VIS}4Map) to identify success and failure modes. This deep learning approach constitutes a major step forward in engineering and understanding of {RNA} synthetic biology.}, 
  pages    = {872077}, 
  note     = {Read on 19.12.15 
The authors use Sort-Seq in E. coli to measure the activities of {\textasciitilde} 244k (though only {\textasciitilde} 100k in pactice) different candidate toehold riboswitches. They then fit an {MLP} {DNN} to these data (one-hot encoded 145 nt sequence as input, either regression or classification as output), and found that this worked better than a bunch of other models, including models based on biochemical features. 

I think the paper's {OK}, but there are a number of issues that should be addressed. In particular, they don't cite me. I'm going to write and send a critique (below).
------
Email to Jim collins on 19.12.17:

Hi Jim,

I've just read your preprint,

Angenent-Mari et al. (2019) Deep Learning for {RNA} Synthetic Biology. {bioRxiv} doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.1101/872077

The use of deep neural networks for analyzing the data produced by massively parallel reporter assays is an area of great interest for me, so I figured it made sense to send you my feedback (see below). Please feel free to share these comments with your co-authors. I'm also happy to field additional questions if you like. 

Cheers, 
-Justin

  Justin B. Kinney
  Assistant Professor
  Simons Center for Quantitative Biology
  Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory
  jkinney@cshl.edu
  631-897-5731

I have two primary critiques:

First, there are a number of important references that are missing from your manuscript. The experimental method you describe is a well-established massively parallel reporter assay called "Sort-Seq". This method was introduced by Kinney et al. (2010) and has since been used by many groups to study a wide range of regulatory mechanisms; see Peterman \&amp; Levine (2016) or Kinney \&amp; {McCandlish} (2019) for reviews. In particular, multiple papers dating back to at least Homqvist et al. (2013) and Peterman et al. (2014) have used Sort-Seq to dissect the mechanisms of regulatory {RNA} structures in bacteria. Some of this prior work has even performed explicit comparisons to calculations of {RNA} duplex and hairpin \${\textbackslash} Delta G\$ values, which seem relevant to your results. As currently written, the Introduction and Discussion of your manuscript give the incorrect impression that Sort-Seq method itself is novel. There is a citation to a 2013 paper from the Church lab, but this acknowledgement is only provided in the Methods section and it fails to communicate either the correct origins of Sort-Seq or how well-established this approach is, even within the bacterial regulatory {RNA} and synthetic biology communities (see also Cambry et al., 2018).

Second, I'm concerned about the way that Sort-Seq data is being used to quantify both expression (i.e. {ON} and {OFF} values) and inducibility ({ON}/{OFF}). {ON} and {OFF} values are said to be estimates of mean bin number, affinely transformed so that they fall in the interval [0,1]. This rescaling obscures the true dynamic range (i.e. log fold-change) of your expression measurements, which is important for readers to know. Of more concern to me is the {ON}/{OFF} ratio, which is computed as the difference between these {ON} and {OFF} values. If {ON} and {OFF} values had not been rescaled, then such a difference would indeed provide a measure of the log fold-change. But the rescaling that is used  corrupts this interpretation, producing values that are not monotonically related to log fold-change. This data transformation is likely, I think, to effectively add systematic noise to the data on which you train your models. It also makes it harder for readers to interpret the predictions of the models you infer. 

Finally, I noticed that the middle panel of Fig. 1 appears to be adapted without citation from Fig. 1 of Peterman et al. (2016). 

References:

Cambray, G., Guimaraes, J., Arkin, A. (2018). Evaluation of 244,000 synthetic sequences reveals design principles to optimize translation in Escherichia coli. Nat Biotechnol 157(10), 624 - 1015. https://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nbt.4238

Holmqvist, E., {ReimegŒrd}, J., Wagner, E. (2013). Massive functional mapping of a 5'-{UTR} by saturation mutagenesis, phenotypic sorting and deep sequencing. Nucl Acids Res 41(12), e122. https://dx.doi.org/10.1093/nar/gkt267

Kinney, J., Murugan, A., Callan, C., Cox, E. (2010). Using deep sequencing to characterize the biophysical mechanism of a transcriptional regulatory sequence Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences 107(20), 9158-9163. https://dx.doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1004290107

Kinney, J., {McCandlish}, D. (2019). Massively Parallel Assays and Quantitative {SequenceÐFunction} Relationships Annual Review of Genomics and Human Genetics 20(1), 99-127. https://dx.doi.org/10.1146/annurev-genom-083118-014845

Peterman, N., Lavi-Itzkovitz, A., Levine, E. (2014). Large-scale mapping of sequence-function relations in small regulatory {RNAs} reveals plasticity and modularity. Nucl Acids Res 42(19), 12177 - 12188. https://dx.doi.org/10.1093/nar/gku863

Peterman, N., Levine, E. (2016). Sort-seq under the hood: implications of design choices on large-scale characterization of sequence-function relations. {BMC} Genomics 17(1), 206. https://dx.doi.org/10.1186/s12864-016-2533-5}
}

